@tamkaho 
Hello tamkaho,  augmentation applied both on images and ground truth(without saving them to disk) can be achieved by keras.preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(), and then use flow() or flow_from_directory() method. A detail example can be found in keras documents, which shows how to do the augmentation: [https://keras.io/preprocessing/image/](example)

I have already implemented this in my own project. But I would like to use Augmentor library to do it , ,because for my own dataset, this augmentation effect is better than the keras built-in library I mentioned above.

I would not change the documentation as it is, instead it could make sense to add a section "For the impatient" to the README, http://decorator.readthedocs.io/en/latest/README.html
It could contain this example:
```python
# an example of how to define a family of decorators warning in the log file if an operation is too slow
from decorator import decorator

@decorator
def warn_slow(func, timelimit=60, *args, **kw):
    t0 = time.time()
    result = func(*args, **kw)
    dt = time.time() - t0
    if dt > timelimit:
        logging.warn('%s took %d seconds', func.__name__, dt)
    else:
        logging.info('%s took %d seconds', func.__name__, dt)
    return result

@warn_slow  # warn if it takes more than 1 minute
def preprocess_input_files(input_dir):
    ...

@warn_slow(timelimit=600)  # warn if it takes more than 10 minutes
def run_full_calculation(tempdir, outdir):
    ...
```
What do you think?

I have the same complaint:

It makes the use of the library prone to bugs, because code down the line can mess up the root `db` in an unpredictable way.

It's event more of a trap because it reads like idiomatic javascript chains but runs very differently:

```javascript
// Usual D3 code IIRC
var body = d3.select("body");
var h1 = body.append("h1");
var h2 = body.append("h2");

// Pyrebase
users = db.child("users")
a = users.child("john")
b = users.child("paul")
```

h2 points to `body h2`
b points to `users/john/paul`


Same thing for filtering, mutations are unexpected.

https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.10/topics/db/queries/#filtered-querysets-are-unique

Something like:
```python
class Database:
    ...
    @classmethod
    def _sub(cls, x, query=None, path=None):
        """Clone/Factory, naive implem, could use a Query object instead"""
        d = cls(x.credentials, ...)
        
        if path is not None:
            d.path = path 
        if query is not None:
            d.query = query
            
        return d

    def child(self, *path):
        suffix = "/".join([str(p) for p in path])

        if suffix.startswith("/"):
            suffix = suffix[1:]

        new_path = self.path + "/" + suffix

        return self._sub(self, path=new_path)

    def _with_query_param(self, name, value):
        return self._sub(self, query=dict(self.query, **{name: value}))

    def order_by_child(self, order):
        return self._with_query_param('orderBy', order)
    ...
```

would help.

Hi Nick,

This covers a webfont and relative paths. I'm stuck using hashed images using absolute paths, like so:
`background: url("/static/img/gmlogo.png");`
I would need a way to add the hash to the filename, so in the final css the line would become:
`background: url("/static/img/gmlogo.eb9b2e437a309c901e9f40f638b06bba.png");`

Is the `~!file!` prefix something webpack recognises in the build process? If so, I gather I would need to set up some additional processing in my webpack.config.js to get it to add the hash to my css urls? I don't think it currently even processes css files.

My config currently looks like this:

```
var path = require('path');
var ManifestRevisionPlugin = require('manifest-revision-webpack-plugin');

var rootAssetPath = './app/resources/';

module.exports = {
  entry: './app/resources/js/app.js',
  output: {
    filename: '/js/bundle.js',
    path: path.resolve(__dirname, './app/static')
  },
  module: {
    loaders: [
      {
        test: /\.(jpe?g|png|gif|svg|ico)$/i,
        loaders: [
            'file-loader?context=' + rootAssetPath + '&name=[path][name].[hash].[ext]'
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  plugins: [
    new ManifestRevisionPlugin(path.join('app/static', 'manifest.json'), {
        rootAssetPath: rootAssetPath,
        ignorePaths: ['css', 'js', 'font']
    })
  ]
};
```

The app structure looks like this:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2543276/28916248-dead9572-7841-11e7-9fff-bbf8cc6d7482.png)

Thanks, I appreciate your help.

