@twiecki I see your point, but I guess I'm torn.  I think we want pyfolio to be particularly user-friendly to the coding 'naive' user (e.g. the Finance guy who lives in Excel), so failing gracefully with no exceptions via passing over stuff that doesn't work seems right to me.  Obviously if we could catch every potential bad input and handle it properly that would be great, however given how restrictive pandas/matplotlib/etc is with handling timezones/DateTimeIndex's, etc, I think this will be difficult and frustrating for anyone not up the Python learning curve.  TBH even I had much difficulty just trying to pass in some naive daily returns with simple datestamps, until I spent some time figuring out how to modify timezone settings and normalize/localize DateTimeIndex's.  

Maybe we need a 'debug' setting/flag for developers/programming quants that operates in the better state which you've described (throwing exceptions, etc), but if it's set to 'false' (for the non-coder user) it just passes over exceptions and fails gracefully, but still generates all possible plots.

